<p><b>Socioeconomic status</b> (SES) is an economic and sociological 
combined total measure of a person's work experience and of an 
individual's or family’s economic and social position relative to 
others, based on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">income</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Education" title="Education">education</a>, and occupation. When analyzing a family’s SES, the household income, earners' <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Education" title="Education">education</a>, and occupation are examined, as well as combined income, versus with an individual, when their own attributes are assessed.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Socioeconomic status is typically broken into three categories, high 
SES, middle SES, and low SES to describe the three areas a family or an 
individual may fall into. When placing a family or individual into one 
of these categories any or all of the three variables (income, 
education, and occupation) can be assessed.</p>
<p>A fourth variable, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wealth" title="Wealth">wealth</a>, may also be examined when determining socioeconomic status.</p>
<p>Additionally, low income and little education have shown to be strong
 predictors of a range of physical and mental health problems, ranging 
from respiratory viruses, arthritis, coronary disease, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schizophrenia" title="Schizophrenia">schizophrenia</a>.
 These may be due to environmental conditions in their workplace, or in 
the case of mental illnesses, may be the entire cause of that persons 
social predicament to begin with.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Main Factors">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Main_Factors">Main Factors</span></h2>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Income">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Income">Income</span></h3>
<p><i>Income</i> refers to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wage" title="Wage">wages</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salaries" title="Salaries" class="mw-redirect">salaries</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profit_%28accounting%29" title="Profit (accounting)">profits</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rents" title="Rents" class="mw-redirect">rents</a>, and any flow of earnings received. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">Income</a>
 can also come in the form of unemployment or workers compensation, 
social security, pensions, interests or dividends, royalties, trusts, 
alimony, or other governmental, public, or family financial assistance.</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">Income</a> can be looked at in two terms, relative and absolute. Absolute income, as theorized by economist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Maynard_Keynes" title="John Maynard Keynes">John Maynard Keynes</a>, is the relationship in which as <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">income</a> increases, so will consumption, but not at the same rate.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_poverty" title="Relative poverty" class="mw-redirect">Relative income</a>
 dictates a person or family’s savings and consumption based on the 
family’s income in relation to others. Income is a commonly used measure
 of SES because it is relatively easy to figure for most individuals.</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income_inequality" title="Income inequality" class="mw-redirect">Income inequality</a> is most commonly measured around the world by the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gini_coefficient" title="Gini coefficient">Gini coefficient</a>,
 where 0 corresponds to perfect equality and 1 means perfect inequality.
 Low income families focus on meeting immediate needs and do not 
accumulate wealth that could be passed on to future generations, thus 
increasing inequality. Families with higher and expendable income can 
accumulate <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wealth" title="Wealth">wealth</a> and focus on meeting immediate needs while being able to consume and enjoy luxuries and weather crises.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>

<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">

<p>Education also plays a role in income. Median earnings increase with each level of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Education" title="Education">education</a>.
 As conveyed in the chart, the highest degrees, professional and 
doctoral degrees, make the highest weekly earnings while those without a
 high school diploma earn less. Higher levels of education are 
associated with better economic and psychological outcomes (i.e.: more 
income, more control, and greater social support and networking).<sup id="cite_ref-apa_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apa-6"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Education plays a major role in skill sets for acquiring jobs, as 
well as specific qualities that stratify people with higher SES from 
lower SES. Annette Lareau speaks on the idea of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concerted_cultivation" title="Concerted cultivation">concerted cultivation</a>, where <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_class" title="Middle class">middle class</a>
 parents take an active role in their children’s education and 
development by using controlled organized activities and fostering a 
sense of entitlement through encouraged discussion. Laureau argues that 
families with lower income do not participate in this movement, causing 
their children to have a sense of constraint. A division in education 
attainment is thus born out of these two differences in child rearing. 
Lower income families can have children who do not succeed to the levels
 of the middle income children, who can have a greater sense of 
entitlement, be more argumentative, or be better prepared for adult 
life.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Occupation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Occupation">Occupation</span></h3>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_prestige" title="Occupational prestige">Occupational prestige</a> as one component of SES, encompasses both <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">income</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Educational_attainment" title="Educational attainment">educational attainment</a>.
 Occupational status reflects the educational attainment required to 
obtain the job and income levels that vary with different jobs and 
within ranks of occupations. Additionally, it shows achievement in 
skills required for the job. Occupational status measures social 
position by describing job characteristics, decision making ability and 
control, and psychological demands on the job.</p>
<p>Occupations are ranked by the Census (among other organizations) and 
opinion polls from the general population are surveyed. Some of the most
 prestigious occupations are physicians and surgeons, lawyers, chemical 
and biomedical engineers, and communications analysts. These jobs, 
considered to be grouped in the high SES classification, provide more 
challenging work and ability and greater control over working 
conditions. Those jobs with lower rankings were food preparation 
workers, counter attendants, bartenders and helpers, dishwashers, 
janitors, maids and housekeepers, vehicle cleaners, and parking lot 
attendants. The jobs that were less valued were also paid significantly 
less and are more laborious,very hazardous, and provide less autonomy.<sup id="cite_ref-apa_6-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apa-6"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Occupation is the most difficult factor to measure because so many 
exist, and there are so many competing scales. Many scales rank 
occupations based on the level of skill involved, from unskilled to 
skilled manual labor to professional, or use a combined measure using 
the education level needed and income involved.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Other Variables">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Other_Variables">Other Variables</span></h2>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Wealth">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Wealth">Wealth</span></h3>
<p><i>Wealth</i>, a set of economic reserves or assets, presents a 
source of security providing a measure of a household's ability to meet 
emergencies, absorb economic shocks, or provide the means to live 
comfortably. Wealth reflects intergenerational transitions as well as 
accumulation of income and savings.<sup id="cite_ref-apa_6-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apa-6"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income" title="Income">Income</a>, age, marital status, family size, religion, occupation, and education are all predictors for wealth attainment.</p>
<p>The wealth gap, like income inequality, is very large in the United 
States. There exists a racial wealth gap due in part to income 
disparities and differences in achievement. According to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Shapiro" title="Thomas Shapiro">Thomas Shapiro</a>,
 differences in savings (due to different rates of incomes), inheritance
 factors, and discrimination in the housing market lead to the racial 
wealth gap. Shapiro claims that savings increase with increasing income,
 but African Americans cannot participate in this, because they make 
significantly less than whites. Additionally, rates of inheritance 
dramatically differ between African Americans and whites. The amount a 
person inherits, either during a lifetime or after death, can create 
different starting points between two different individuals or families.
 These different starting points also factor into housing, education, 
and employment discrimination. A third reason Shapiro offers for the 
racial wealth gap are the various discriminations African Americans must
 face, like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redlining" title="Redlining">redlining</a>
 and higher interest rates in the housing market. These types of 
discrimination feed into the other reasons why African Americans end up 
having different starting points and therefore fewer assets.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Socioeconomic_status&action=edit&section=6" title="Edit section: Psychological Effects">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Psychological_Effects">Psychological Effects</span></h2>
<p>A study published in the December 2008 issue of <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychological_Science_%28journal%29" title="Psychological Science (journal)">Psychological Science</a></i>
 found that children of parents with a high socioeconomic status tended 
to express more "disengagement" behaviors than their less fortunate 
peers. In this context, disengagement behaviors represents actions such 
as fidgeting with other objects and drawing pictures while being 
addressed. Other participants born into less favored circumstances 
tended to make more <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_contact" title="Eye contact">eye contact</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nod_%28gesture%29" title="Nod (gesture)">head nods</a>
 and signs of happiness when put into an interactive social environment.
 Authors hypothesize that the more fortuitous peers felt less inclined 
to gain <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rapport" title="Rapport">rapport</a> with their group because they saw no need for their assistance in the future.<sup id="cite_ref-Kraus2008_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kraus2008-11"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
